      "content": "that makes sense from their perspective. but looking at it from the other side, critics often say originalism is basically just a \"living constitution\" approach in disguise—they argue that judges just pick whichever historical fact supports the conservative outcome they want anyway. do you think originalism can actually be a neutral way to interpret the law, or is it inherently tied to a certain political ideology?",
